Midgaard's relationship to the Great Pyramid is scholarly and commercial. City archives hold expedition charter records and trade documentation for goods of pyramid-complex provenance. The pyramid's administrative technology — ledger priests maintaining tribute records, census counts, and legal testimony in an integrated archive — is recognized as a predecessor to Midgaard's civic record practices. Current concern: pyramid-origin relics circulating in desert caravan markets require provenance documentation verifying they are not Correction-class artifacts with deliberately altered inscriptions. The Jackal Synod's presence throughout the pyramid complex means access to specific archive layers requires either Synod clearance (politically unacceptable) or force (logistically difficult).

