The Great Pyramid is preserved in Rakuen community oral tradition primarily through Khenari and Ushabti cultural transmission. Both communities maintain accounts of the Solar Court and the funerary adjudication system that are more detailed than any city archive account because they descend from within the tradition rather than from outside observers. Rakuen's Khenari community holds the pyramid's death-rite geography as sacred: the weighing chambers, funerary boat representations, and directional orientation of the burial galleries are preserved as functional sacred geography even among community members who have never visited the site.

