Khenari death-rite geography at the Great Pyramid identifies the weighing chambers as the institutional formalization of funerary judgment that Khenari tradition preserves in its most precise ritual form. The Jackal Tribunal's three sentence classes correspond to three Khenari outcome categories in death-judgment tradition. The Correction sentence class — memory rewritten for political continuity — is in Khenari tradition the specific abomination the weighing ceremony is designed to prevent: no institutional authority should have the power to alter what the dead know about themselves. The fact that the late Solar Court's Jackal Tribunal systematically performed Corrections proves, in Khenari reading, that the institution had ceased to perform death-rites and had become their inverse — a machine for producing false souls rather than for honestly assessing real ones.
